Quackerjack

Target IP: 192.168.182.57

Scanning


There are eight TCP ports open on the target machine. Performing an aggressive scan shows FTP has a timeout issue. Looks like HTTP, SMB, MySQL, and HTTP on port 8081 are the most interesting.

Enumeration

Port 8081: HTTPS

After enumerating the different ports, I did not find anything. However, this port is interesting. Doing a directory search leads to the interesting result above. The command I used is gobuster dir -u https://192.168.182.57:8081 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -s 200 -x php,html,txt -k -b "".


The login webpage above is displayed for this port. The version and name of the application is rConfig 3.9.4.


This application is vulnerable to SQL injection. And I found the exploit for this application using searchsploit. Time to leverage this exploit to land a foothold on the machine.

Exploitation


Only the first exploit worked against the target machine. I tried the other two first, but I had no luck. After running the first exploit, I obtained admin:1:dc40b85276a1f4d7cb35f154236aa1b2 as shown above. The password of the user admin is in MD5 and after decrypting it, I obtained the password abgrtyu.


Now I have access to the application on port 8081 using the username admin and password abgrtyu.


And now I have a foothold on the machine using the exploit with the EDB-ID of 47982.

Privilege Escalation


Looks like /usr/bin/find has SUID bit set!


And now I have a root shell.

Flags


The proof.txt flag once I used find binary to spawn a root shell. I forgot to screenshot the local.txt flag here, but I did manage to submit the flag.
